{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17628287","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17628287"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:55:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:55:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17192"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17192","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17192"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9882"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69301"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9882","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9882"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17192"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54754"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"7615"},{"type":"tags","id":"7620"},{"type":"tags","id":"10697"},{"type":"tags","id":"10748"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23199"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23200"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69301","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/69301"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDNA methylation is an epigenetic process that regulates gene expression in eukaryotic cells.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the process of DNA methylation in eukaryotic cells?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Addition of methyl groups to cytosine bases in CpG sites","Addition of methyl groups to adenine bases","Removal of methyl groups from histone proteins","Addition of acetyl groups to DNA bases","Addition of methyl groups to RNA nucleotides"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAddition of methyl groups to cytosine bases in CpG sites\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct description of DNA methylation. DNA methyltransferase enzymes catalyse the transfer of methyl groups to the 5\u0027 carbon position of cytosine residues, predominantly within CpG dinucleotides, forming 5-methylcytosine.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAddition of methyl groups to adenine bases\u003C/strong\u003E - While this occurs in bacteria, it is not a significant mechanism in eukaryotic DNA methylation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERemoval of methyl groups from histone proteins\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes histone demethylation, a different epigenetic modification\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAddition of acetyl groups to DNA bases\u003C/strong\u003E - This is referring to acetylation, however acetylation typically occurs on histone proteins, not DNA bases\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAddition of methyl groups to RNA nucleotides\u003C/strong\u003E - While RNA can be methylated, this is distinct from DNA methylation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDNA methylation typically results in transcriptional repression by preventing transcription factor binding and recruiting repressive protein complexes to modified sites. This mechanism is crucial for processes such as X chromosome inactivation, genomic imprinting, and gene silencing.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["DNA methylation typically occurs at cytosine bases within CpG dinucleotides to regulate gene expression.","DNA methyltransferase enzymes add methyl groups to the 5\u0027 carbon of cytosine to form 5-methylcytosine.","DNA methylation generally leads to transcriptional repression by preventing transcription factor binding and recruiting repressive complexes."],"references":["Turnpenny PD, Ellard S. Emery\u0027s Elements of Medical Genetics E-Book: Elsevier Health Sciences; 2011","Robert J Schmitz, Zachary A Lewis, Mary G Goll, DNA methylation: shared and divergent features across eukaryotes, https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC6825889/, 2020"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54754"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17192"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54754","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/54754"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-11T18:47:47+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-11T18:49:25+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9882"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69301"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationsh